{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17497083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17497083"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:03:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:03:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1469"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1469"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.03,0.66,0.09,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1469"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31711"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1469"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1469"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17469"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"767"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6636"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6923"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38106"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31711"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner (GP) due to ongoing ankle pain following an injury at social frisbee 10 weeks ago. He says the original injury occurred when his foot \u0027twisted inwards\u0027 in an inversion movement. He was unable to weight-bear at the time of the injury and mobilised on crutches for the following two weeks. He did not seek medical attention until this point. He is a heavy smoker and states that he goes through a \u0022pack a day roughly\u0022 since he was 16. On examination, there is tenderness to palpation over the lateral malleolus with pain on active and passive ankle eversion. Peripheral pulses and sensation is intact. An X-ray of the joint is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Medial ligament tear","Osteoarthritis of the ankle","Healing lateral malleolar fracture","Accessory ossicle","Medial malleolus fracture"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehealing lateral malleolar fracture\u003C/strong\u003E. The fragment is rounded and corticated, signifying that it has undergone healing and is not a new fracture. The tenderness experienced by the patient would be localised to the scar tissue holding the fragment to the malleolus. The significant smoking history is a major risk factor in delaying the healing of this fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial ligament tear\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be caused by the mechanism of injury described in the stem. Additionally, given the radiological evidence of the healing fracture it is unlikely to be the cause of the pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoarthritis of the ankle \u003C/strong\u003Eis degenerative joint disease of the tibio-talar joint that is a far less common form of osteoarthritis than that of the knee and hip joints. Post-traumatic arthritis accounts for approximately 2/3 of the reported cases of ankle osteoarthritis. Radiological findings include asymmetrical loss of joint space, osteophyte formation, subchondral sclerosis and subchondral cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccessory ossicles\u003C/strong\u003E around the foot and ankle are common skeletal variations, usually derived from the failure of union of secondary ossification centers adjacent to the main bone. They might be either adjacent to the main bone or separated. These accessory ossicles are often mistaken for fractures and are asymptomatic but can occasionally become symptomatic following injury. Given the history of trauma and the healing fracture evident on radiography this is less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial malleolus fracture\u003C/strong\u003E would be less likely given the mechanism of injury and the absence of radiological findings consistent with this fracture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Smoking is a major risk factor for delayed bone healing, especially fractures of the lower limb"],"references":["Patel RA, Wilson RF, Patel PA, Palmer RM. The effect of smoking on bone healing: A systematic review. Bone Joint Res. 2013 Jun 14;2(6):102-11. doi: 10.1302/2046-3758.26.2000142. PMID: 23836474; PMCID: PMC3686151.","Keles-Celik N, Kose O, Sekerci R, Aytac G, Turan A, G\u00fcler F. Accessory Ossicles of the Foot and Ankle: Disorders and a Review of the Literature. Cureus. 2017 Nov 26;9(11):e1881. doi: 10.7759/cureus.1881. PMID: 29387510; PMCID: PMC5786346."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17469"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1469"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18906"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18906"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c7a55d44-57fe-406a-8542-60b7b2c82423.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c7a55d44-57fe-406a-8542-60b7b2c82423.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":614,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17469"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-01-20T13:06:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-07T20:23:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1469"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"3